Oftentimes, our idea of what a healthy amount of body fat is to us is different than what our body’s idea of a healthy body fat percentage is.

We need to balance our expectations with reality for the sake of our health.

There is no “right” amount of fat.

A healthy amount of body fat for us is where we sit comfortably and maintain with ease while still:

✨ Eating plenty of calories and nutrients from the right sources.

✨ Have a strong ovulation and regular period aka maintain our fertility.

✨ Have strong body temperature & pulse, good moods, sleep, hair, brain function, libido, digestion & energy.

✨ Are able to move around comfortably all day without our weight impeding our joints or our ability to be active and live our life to the fullest.

Keep in mind, women of childbearing years, often naturally sit at a body fat percentage of 25%-35%.

Now, of course there are exceptions to this and some women can still achieve health when they are “leaner”, but often, genetics, metabolic health and muscle mass play a larger role in this being possible.

Keep in mind, how long your torso is, the size of your ribcage and the length of your legs will also make the same amount of body fat appear different from woman to woman.

If you have to fight your body to maintain a weight and are constantly in the mindset of “getting back” to your former self, chances are you’re probably at a more comfortable weight for your body now than you were back then.

There is such a thing as “having excess fat”, but that is not determined by having rolls or bra overhang or a pooch when you sit down.

All stomachs roll/fold when we sit. 

And praaiiissssee theee Loorrrdd for that or life would be uncomfortable and your skin would feel like a rubber band about to snap. 

Make sure your leave room in your “flat stomach” expectations for your rib cage, your organs, your uterus and a protective layer around your organs!

Do you want to know why the metabolism IS the root cause?

Well let's start by asking, what IS our metabolism?

Simply put, it is how well our cells use energy to do the jobs they are supposed to do.

The metabolism is the rate at which we convert calories and oxygen into energy AND how efficiently and effectively we use that fuel.

It doesn't just affect how we gain and lose weight, it also affects how we function down to the cells themselves.

And every part of our body is made up of... CELLS.

And since hormones are made BY cells FOR cells (simply cellular messengers), it affects both our hormonal output and how we receive and respond to hormones.

Our metabolism affects:

〰️ Detoxification (liver, skin, kidneys, etc.)

〰️ Digestion

〰️ Thyroid

〰️ Adrenals

〰️ Pancreas (enzymes & insulin)

〰️ Menstrual Cycle/Reproduction

〰️ Insulin Sensitivity

〰️ Inflammation

〰️ Immune System

This is why focusing on diets and protocols that suppress  symptoms like weight gain or autoimmunity is a bandaid that often makes metabolic function worse in the long run.

This is why so many people share that symptoms go away for a while and then come back worse than before.

Heal your metabolism, heal your whole self.

Many factors affect our metabolism including our nutrition, the frequency of our nutrition, our mental state/emotions, our breathing, our nervous system, our movement, our environment, etc.

How do we get started?

🍑Nourish our bodies vs. restrict from our bodies

🍑Provide enough calories from a balance of protein, carbs and fat

🍑Take deep breaths

🍑Make stress reduction and down time (doing "nothing") a priority

🍑Eat frequently & consistently

🍑Prioritize sleep

🍑Don't ignore your emotional needs

Did you know that healthy livers need sugar to function?!

A lot of people think that the liver is a filter. This WRONG. It is our metabolic regulator- the battery pack of the body.

It performs over 500 functions, including breaking down toxins and used up hormones and getting them where they need to go, so they can get the heck out of the body.

One of the liver's main jobs is to maintain our blood sugar levels.

When we aren't eating, we actually don't run on thin air (shocking, I know).

Our cells need a steady supply of glucose to do all the things they need to do. And since our liver can store up glucose in the storage form of glycogen, it will steadily turn this storage glucose into actual glucose and release it into the bloodstream to feed the cells.

This keeps our body from having to use stress hormones like cortisol to break down our own tissue and turn it into sugar.

But you see, the liver needs to be HEALTHY to be able to store up enough glucose to keep us going during long periods without eating.

It needs to be provided a steady stream of glucose regularly, so it can fill itself up. It also needs many nutrients like protein, B vitamins,Vitamin C, Vitamin E, Vitamin A and many minerals.

When our hormones are imbalanced and our stress is high, our liver has a hard time keeping blood sugar stable and can only go a few hours. So why do you wake up around 2am? YOU HAVE LOW BLOOD SUGAR

Your body needs fuel or it will start breaking itself down.

The quickest way to fall back asleep is to have a bit of sugar like a spoonful of honey or add some protein, like: -a piece of cheese and some honey

-a glass of milk with some maple syrup

-a glass of OJ with a scoop of collagen

-a piece of fruit and few bites of cottage cheese

Then, your fight or flight turns off, you body can relax back into deep sleep. Waking up (or waking up to pee constantly) in the wee hours of the morning is a sure sign that the liver is having to pick up the slack of our roller coaster blood sugar.

One sign of being a healthy woman is being able to sleep soundly throughout the night (when the opportunity presents itself mommas).

node.text:
Put your hands up if you've ever heard "you don't need carbs, your body will just make them" (hand emoji, hand emoji, different colored skin tones)

Yes, your body can make many things it needs when stuck in a survival state or famine, that doesn't mean its GOOD for it.

Where do you think this fuel comes from?

Gluconeogenesis is the technical term for the synthesizing (creation) of glucose.

Because the liver and muscles can only store so much glucose as glycogen, once its used up, its time to manufacture.

This requires catabolism, aka the eating of yourself.

It is a very inflammatory and stressful process- it requires the stress hormone cortisol to elevate, break down our existing tissue (like muscle, glands, organs, connective tissues, etc.), send it to the liver to be turned into glucose.

Glucose is then secreted into the bloodstream, where the cells will then take it up and the mitochondria will manufacture a cell fuel called ATP.

The problem with most people today, is that they've put their body through this process for so long, their liver can barely store enough sugar to get them through a few hours after their meal.

Not only is the liver unable to store sugar well, but gluconeogenesis quickly depletes the liver of vital nutrients it needs to function like, Taurine, Magnesium, B Vitamins, copper & Vitamin A to name a few.

The minute blood sugar drops, cortisol rises- you may feel hungry, you may not (stress suppresses your hunger signals). But you definitely start to feel anxious, irritable, snappy, tired, emotional, get a headache and unable to regulate your temperatures.

This, my dear, is/was the beginning of all your hormonal imbalances.

Hypoglycemia is usually at the root of almost every thyroid, adrenal, hormonal, gut and inflammatory condition.

The fix? Stop forcing your body make its own sugar. Eat balanced meals that contain protein and carb every couple of hours from within 30 minutes of waking until 30 minutes before bed. Watch your body shift in front of your very eyes.

Some women can't even make it through their night without their liver running out of sugar (hello 2am wake up).

EAT!

Waking up nauseous is absolutely NO fun, but many women do.

They let this keep them from eating breakfast, when in reality, the only thing that will help is BALANCING YOUR BLOOD SUGAR.

With food. If you missed that the only way to balance blood sugar is with FOOD.

You see, morning nausea often points to blood sugar issues, but can also be a sign that the liver needs a bit of support.

A good example of this is women in their first trimester of pregnancy as their blood volume is rapidly increasing, so is their need for minerals (specifically sodium) and bioavailable protein- leading to intense blood sugar drops.

Oftentimes, morning nausea is an escalated version of waking up with no appetite, which usually points to a body that has high stress hormones.

If you haven’t taken my free blood sugar training yet (link in bio), to recap, adrenal hormones like cortisol help manipulate blood sugar to keep the body surviving when there’s not enough fuel coming in.

When our blood sugar is on a roller coaster all day and then we go to bed and fast, this doesn’t manually “fix” our blood sugar.

In fact, it forces our body to make fuel by eating itself! (This is called catabolism FYI)

This might mean a night of poor sleep that night or a poor morning appetite the next day, or more blood sugar swings that week or feeling super tired and annoyed the following day.

How to support?
✨Start balancing your blood sugar by eating writhing 30-60 minutes of waking and then eating protein, carb and fat every 3-4 hours!
✨Don’t expect it to go away over night! It can take a few weeks for the morning appetite to balance out
✨Spend 5-10 minutes taking some deep belly breaths to get yourself out of that fight or flight state and into rest and digest (especially important for mouth breathers)
✨Have a little warm water or tea with some lemon/lime/orange, raw honey and a pinch of salt to get things moving.
✨Support your liver using all the tips in my free liver detox guide! (link in bio)

node.text:
As you’ve probably realized by now, not having an appetite in the morning is NOT a good thing.

It's definitely something that we should be working to fix and NOT something we want to cater to.

You see, our body has been fasting since our last meal or snack. 10, 12, 14 hours goes by- we should be HUNGRY.

A healthy liver can hold enough stored glucose (glycogen) for about 8-10 hours until it has to start tapping into other means of fuel.

If our appetite is non existent in the morning, we can pretty much assume, we've already been making our own fuel using cortisol for a couple of hours.

Hello belly fat. Hello suppressed metabolism. Hello hormone issues. Hello poor blood sugar.

Dutch test cortisol levels low when you wake up? Usually a sign we had our cortisol spike a few hours ago.

Most women wakeup around 2-3am when they have hormone issues. It is no coincidence that this falls around 7-9 hours after dinner.

It's just your body sending a signal that it needs some fuel.

A little protein and carb before bed usually helps this:
- 2 softboiled eggs and a cup of strawberries
-1 Cup Goat Milk with some honey
-A few slices of roast beef & some rice crackers
-Sprouted oats with milk & a little butter
-Berries with fresh whipped cream with a bit of collagen mixed in
-Homemade marshmallows
-Cup of bone broth and a small baked potato with butter

And regardless of how we feel, we should be eating within 30-60 minutes of waking to provide our body with fuel. Eventually,, hunger comes back.

“What about if I’m nauseous in the morning?” I’ll be doing a reel about this tomorrow 😊

I call this “the rollover effect.”

Our choices today determine if we go into tomorrow replenished and ready to face the stressors of tomorrow or…

just a little bit depleted and less resilient to stress than the day before.

I had a lot of you asking if eating enough throughout the day yesterday could affect how you feel today?

OF COURSE!

Your habits in the present will affect how you feel:
🔸tomorrow
🔸next week
🔸next cycle
🔸your ovulation 100 days from now
🔸your pregnancies in the future
🔸when you go through menopause

Our period is our monthly “report card” and is the time when our body really tells us if our habits are working for us or not.

Keep in mind, it takes 100 days for a dormant follicle in our ovary to make it to ovulation.

That means our ovulation in 3 months is impacted by today’s habits.

Every pregnancy, we give about 10% of our minerals and nutrients to our unborn child- meaning the future generation’s nutrient status is dependent on if we have the nutrients to even give.

If you are struggling now, it’s probably a result of the stressors you’ve faced leading up to now, NOT what you are doing now.

There’s NOTHING wrong with you.

Your body has just been through a lot.

It takes time to get to a place of imbalance and it takes time to get out of it.

Have hope, be encouraged that what you’re doing (nourishing your body) has the potential to change the world and it just takes you focusing on taking one baby step after another. ❤️

Things like:
🍉Eating breakfast
🍉Taking the time to eat a balanced snack every 3-4 hours
🍉 Breathing deep
🍉 Saying “no” more
🍉 Stretching
🍉 Eating enough calories 

may seem small, but are changing the way you show up- in your relationships, as a parent, in your career, in the world.

I know it’s hard, but I want to remind you that it matters.

node.text:
Even though our hair follicles are not technically "organs", these amazing generators of energy require a massive amount of glucose, protein, vitamins and minerals to produce robust and healthy hair.
.
To quote Dr. Roger J. Williams who perfectly summed it up, "The cells in hair follicles produce hair when they are furnished with everything they need. But in the scalp of a balding man, they do not get everything they need and as a result, the hair producing cells gradually die off. Here we have an example of a mild 'disease' which is caused by cellular malnutrition."
.
This is why I always encourage women to no ask the question "how do I stop my hair loss?", but rather "why did it start to happen in the first place?"
.
Hair follicles require ENERGY. They require you to be eating enough carbohydrates, proteins, saturated fats for fat soluble vitamins and plenty of minerals.
.
They are hypersensitive to stressors like high cortisol, low thyroid function (hypothyroidsim), elevated estrogen and elevated serotonin. They are severely sensitive to endotoxin (from bacteria overload in the gut) and prostaglandins (Inflammatory response).
.
Hair, although wonderful, is not essential to our survival. Our body will prioritize things like our hearts and our lungs if it is not getting an abundance of what it needs.
.
Amazing things begin to happen when we start to nourish our body correctly and take the steps to create a better environment for things like hair and skin to flourish.

node.text:
“Stress” is a 3 stage process that describes the physiological changes the body goes through when exposed to stressors, is under strain or in toil.

1. Alarm (Feel great- labs are crap)
2. Resistance (start to feel like crap- labs are normal)
3. Exhaustion (Feel like crap- labs are crap)

Hans Selye, a doctor who specialized in endocrinology his whole life invented the word “stress” after noticing that many of his patients, with different diseases, exhibited identical signs & symptoms.

Selye called this phenomenon of the body responding to the demands placed upon it General Adaptation Syndrome, which normally had 3 phases:

🔶ALARM- the body pulls all its resources and responds to stress with increased focus, energy, drive and all consuming motivation. Depending on how many resources you begin with and how long you can sustain the heightened response, this phase can last 3 weeks or 13 years.

This is why fasting, intense exercise, low carb or keto feels incredible at first or when a stressful event hits, we can barely sleep or stop going going going.

🔶RESISTANCE- you begin to come down from your high of adrenaline. You fell like trash and your cells are struggling from the stressful environment they’ve been forced to endure, but your labs may still be in a “normal” place.

Resources are low and the body is still adapting to the new normal. You might start to see minor signs like cold hands/feet, stubborn fat, PMS, anxiety, digestion issues, headaches, fatigue. If we don’t take steps to replenish, we eventually hit….

🔶EXHAUSTION- our body can no longer maintain balance and starts to adapt and change to keep us going with the limited resources available. This is hypothyroidism, PCOS, insulin resistance, autoimmunity, hormonal imbalances, extreme digestion issues, weight issues, brain fog, depression, hypothalamic amenorrhea, etc. This is where the body is on defense with little resources to spare. THIS IS DISEASE.

The question is not:
“How do I fix XYZ health issue”

The question is “why am I here in the first place and how do I give my body the tools it needs to get back to balance?”

Check out my “stress/adrenals” highlight for more!

Snack alert: Juicy Melon with thinly sliced ham or roast beef 👌🏼

I’ve been really loving this as a pre workout snack lately- it’s light and digests very quick, so it doesn’t sit in your stomach.

FAQ: Do I believe in food combining?

Yes, I believe in combining foods strategically to balance blood sugar and support our thyroid function, so our adrenals and reproductive system can thrive.

Do I believe in collecting arbitrary food rules to make me more confused and overwhelmed than ever when I sit down to eat?

NOPE

Information is widely available these days and more knowledge is not actually making us healthier.

I dare say- it’s making us sicker.

It’s turning an opportunity to nourish ourselves into a scary, fearful, life or death experience.

So how do we know what to believe? What to trust?

The difference between knowledge and WISDOM is a having context to view knowledge with- a BS filter so to speak.

Understanding your physiology and biology IS this filter.

It’s what allows us to approach information with wisdom and empowerment.

Stop collecting food and health rules, jumping from one fad to the next and adding more to your plate- do LESS, focus on what your body NEEDS and build stronger foundations.

Being Fully Nourished is standing firm in the wisdom of your body and not letting anyone convince you that it’s not as wise as they are.

node.text:
Many women complain to me that they are SO tired in the afternoon. They get to a point where they don't want to do anything but take a nap around 2-4pm.

So the first question I ask is "What did you eat today so far?"

Many of the answers go like:
🔸I rolled out of bed and into my day
🔸I didn’t really feel like eating
🔸Went to the kitchen and grabbed a cup of coffee
🔸Went about my stressful morning like a chicken with my head cut off
🔸Had a second cup of coffee and my liquid breakfast 2 hours later 
🔸Kind of snacked?

Ummm negative. Not going to cut it for you GROWN ADULT FEMALE BODY.

If we want our body to function well, we have to fuel it well. We don't put a couple drops of gasoline in a ferrari.

Full tank of gas- always.

Here's what a energy supportive morning looks like:
🍉Wake Up and Eat a nourishing Breakfast Within 30 Minutes that contains protein, carb and fat
🍉Have coffee AFTER you eat ALWAYS
🍉Make sure coffee always has a protein (collagen), carb (sugar) and fat (cream) in it to reduce cortisol
🍉Then go about your stressful day
🍉Eat a snack at the 3 hour mark
🍉Eat lunch 3 hours after that

See if you have an afternoon tantrum, i mean anxiety attack, I mean slump, after that.

We ignore our nourishment? The body will speak to us in other ways 😉

node.text:
After yesterday’s reel, you probably know that losing our appetite can be one of the first signs our body sends us when it’s under stress.

Our hunger hormones get manipulated, so energy can be spent elsewhere.

Blood flows away from the digestive organs to deliver nutrients and oxygen to systems that are more important to survival.

So where does this leave you?

Maybe you lost your appetite a long time ago.

Maybe you thought this was a good thing and encouraged it.

Maybe you never had a strong appetite.

NO TIME LIKE THE PRESENT

I talk about appetite rebound in Fully Nourished and we see this a lot with students.

(For FN students, you can review in lesson 1 of module 4)

The first step is to EAT.

Yep, even if your aren’t hungry.

The only way out is THROUGH.

Appetite rebound is when you first start working to suppress stress hormones by balancing your blood sugar (aka fueling your body appropriately).

It can be challenging at first, but after manually managing blood sugar for a few weeks, appetite often will begin to return as the liver is fueled and stress hormones are a little lower.

Sometimes hunger swings to the opposite end and you feel ravenous for a while- this is okay and GOOD.

The body usually will establish balance.

Don’t stress, there’s nothing wrong with you, it’s just your body trying to communicate!

LISTEN.

What’s your appetite story?
